  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Health procurement Papua New Guinea</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With almost 30 thousand new Tuberculosis cases each year TB has emerged as a public health threat for Papua New Guinea. The Country is facing one of the highest infection rates in the world and National Department of Health  has referred to the situation as a &quot;national emergency.&quot; 

Resurgence of TB in Papua New Guinea has been a result of limited access to adequate healthcare but a result of antibiotic resistance which is currently leading to bacterial resistance and a rise of aggressive strains of the disease, It is believed that a unique strain of drug resistant TB has developed in certain areas of the country, leaving people exposed to more severe infections and a limited menu of treatment options. 

As a rapid and scaled up response to the current crisis, the World Bank in collaboration with the Government of Papua New Guinea, and the National Department of Health, designed the Emergency Tuberculosis Project to both improve the quality and expand coverage of health services in Western Province, Daru Island and National Capital District and strengthen immediate response and treatment of TB. These locations were strategically selected due to the recent sharp rise in the number of new TB infections. 

Two UN agencies, the World Health Organization (WHO) and the united Nations Office for Project Services (UNOPS) will support  National Department of Health in carrying out project activities. UNOPS&apos; objective is to support ensuring timely and efficient availability of TB diagnostics equipment and consumables including but not limited to Gen-expert Machines, mobile clinics wit, digital X-ray machines, and other laboratory, and medical supplies in an attempt to support early detection and treatment of TB patients.</narrative>
  </description>
